messages.content: until we mine our own blocks each time, we can't inject anything into the coinbase
*but* TIDES is great because the reward model has low variance for miners, given they've been mining long enough initially (ramp-up period)
we're going to be renting the hashrate of the pool out and any payments would be disbursed as a reward based on TIDES
and when it's not rented out it'll go to OCEAN where any payouts from that will be disbursed in the same way
doesn't pplns make more sense for selling hashrate
no because you have to have consistent hashrate to have supply
and we're not allowing miners to choose what orders to bid on
it'll be immediately allocated

it's possible to do that later-on, but in-general it's hard to verify work without a central validator.

we're moving to a model where each validator hosts an endpoint and miners would submit shares to a few of them
they'll be recorded and attested to by validators
which distributes the trust of the pool for verifying work
this would allow miners to mine using their own pool hardware as well, in any geography, they just have to submit valid shares to be compensated
do you have a plan to get hashrate back?
the hashrate market should allow us to offer pricing closer to mrr and nh
so we'll be able to profitably attract hashrate rental/arb miners
those that would otherwise sell to either platform or arb through them
doing it non-KYC will also make us attractive to external-miners that just want BTC to their lightning wallet
and purchasers of hashrate that don't want to fill out KYC

B = 5% × min(1, w_h · max(0, 1 - (H / H_target)) + w_p · max(0, 1 - (P / P_target)))
Where:
•  B: The dynamic bonus rate (0% to 5%) applied to miners’ BTC rewards, paid in alpha tokens.
•  w_h: Weight for the hashrate factor (e.g., 0.4); sums with w_p to 1 for balance.
•  w_p: Weight for the price factor (e.g., 0.6).
•  P_target: The target alpha price (e.g., 0.02 TAO), set slightly above current levels with a growth buffer.
•  H_target: The target hashrate (e.g., 1 EH/s), set to encourage progressive growth.

  - Payouts, with full resolution (`miner > payouts`)

- Improved docker builds for validators so updates are propagated quickly.
